WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.220
Welcome to a Deep Dive episode of Jacob's Daily Briefing.

00:00:04.220 --> 00:00:08.440
Today we're doing something a little different. We're putting one

00:00:08.440 --> 00:00:12.660
of the most talked-about A-I forecasting documents under the microscope.

00:00:12.660 --> 00:00:16.880
I'm talking about the A-I twenty-twenty-seven report. If you haven't

00:00:16.880 --> 00:00:21.099
read it, here's the deal. In April twenty-twenty-five, Daniel Kokotajlo,

00:00:21.099 --> 00:00:25.319
a former Open-A-I employee who left the company over safety

00:00:25.319 --> 00:00:29.539
concerns, teamed up with Eli Lifland, Romeo Dean, and Scott

00:00:29.539 --> 00:00:33.759
Alexander to publish a sprawling prediction about where A-I is

00:00:33.759 --> 00:00:37.979
headed. The report laid out a detailed scenario of how

00:00:37.979 --> 00:00:42.199
we'd get from today's frontier models to A-G-I, artificial general

00:00:42.199 --> 00:00:46.419
intelligence, by roughly twenty-twenty-seven. It covered everything: model capabilities, agent

00:00:46.419 --> 00:00:50.639
development, safety risks, geopolitics, the whole works. Now it's been

00:00:50.639 --> 00:00:54.858
almost a year. And I want to answer three questions.

00:00:54.858 --> 00:00:59.078
What did they predict? What have they themselves updated? And

00:00:59.078 --> 00:01:03.298
how does twenty-twenty-six reality compare to their forecast? Let's start

00:01:03.298 --> 00:01:07.518
with the report's core thesis. The central claim was bold.

00:01:07.518 --> 00:01:11.738
A-G-I, defined as A-I systems that can perform virtually all

00:01:11.738 --> 00:01:15.958
economically valuable cognitive work, would arrive around twenty-twenty-seven. Their median

00:01:15.958 --> 00:01:20.178
estimate was late twenty-twenty-six to early twenty-twenty-eight. They argued that

00:01:20.178 --> 00:01:24.398
reasoning models like O-one and O-three represented a new scaling

00:01:24.398 --> 00:01:28.617
paradigm, that A-I agents would move from demos to production

00:01:28.617 --> 00:01:32.837
in twenty-twenty-five and twenty-twenty-six, and that coding A-I would be

00:01:32.837 --> 00:01:37.057
the leading indicator of progress. They also predicted that one

00:01:37.057 --> 00:01:41.277
lab, probably Open-A-I or Anthropic, would pull significantly ahead in

00:01:41.277 --> 00:01:45.497
a winner-take-most dynamic. China would pursue state-directed nationalization of its

00:01:45.497 --> 00:01:49.717
A-I labs. And governments would be caught flat-footed, unable to

00:01:49.717 --> 00:01:53.937
regulate fast enough. On safety, they warned that alignment problems

00:01:53.937 --> 00:01:58.157
would become increasingly visible but would be rationalized away by

00:01:58.157 --> 00:02:02.376
labs racing to deploy. And perhaps most dramatically, they predicted

00:02:02.376 --> 00:02:06.596
recursive self-improvement, A-I systems meaningfully accelerating their own development. That's

00:02:06.596 --> 00:02:10.816
a lot of claims. So how have they held up?

00:02:10.816 --> 00:02:15.036
Let's talk about the biggest update first. The authors' own

00:02:15.036 --> 00:02:19.256
revision. Daniel Kokotajlo himself has publicly pushed his median A-G-I

00:02:19.256 --> 00:02:23.476
estimate from twenty-twenty-seven out to approximately twenty-twenty-nine to twenty-thirty. Let

00:02:23.476 --> 00:02:27.696
me repeat that. The guy who named his report "A-I

00:02:27.696 --> 00:02:31.916
twenty-twenty-seven" now thinks A-G-I is three years further out than

00:02:31.916 --> 00:02:36.136
his original estimate. And he did this within less than

00:02:36.136 --> 00:02:40.355
a year of publishing. Why the revision? Four main reasons.

00:02:40.355 --> 00:02:44.575
First, scaling laws are hitting diminishing returns sooner than expected.

00:02:44.575 --> 00:02:48.795
You can't just make models bigger and expect smooth capability

00:02:48.795 --> 00:02:53.015
gains. Second, inference-time compute scaling through reasoning models is real

00:02:53.015 --> 00:02:57.235
but hasn't produced the exponential leaps some predicted. Third, getting

00:02:57.235 --> 00:03:01.455
A-I agents to work reliably in production is just really

00:03:01.455 --> 00:03:05.675
hard. Benchmarks don't capture the messiness of real-world deployment. And

00:03:05.675 --> 00:03:09.895
fourth, organizational inertia. Even when A-I can technically do a

00:03:09.895 --> 00:03:14.114
task, actually deploying it to replace human workflows involves enormous

00:03:14.114 --> 00:03:18.334
organizational, legal, and trust barriers that the report didn't adequately

00:03:18.334 --> 00:03:22.554
account for. That three-year revision is itself one of the

00:03:22.554 --> 00:03:26.774
most important data points in this whole discussion. If the

00:03:26.774 --> 00:03:30.994
most bullish people in the room are pushing their estimates

00:03:30.994 --> 00:03:35.214
back by three years after just twelve months of new

00:03:35.214 --> 00:03:39.434
evidence, that tells you the uncertainty is genuinely massive. Now,

00:03:39.434 --> 00:03:43.654
let's give credit where it's due. Here's what the report

00:03:43.654 --> 00:03:47.873
got right. First, the agent development trajectory. They nailed this

00:03:47.873 --> 00:03:52.093
directionally. A-I agents have indeed moved from demos to production.

00:03:52.093 --> 00:03:56.313
Claude with computer use, Open-A-I's Operator, Google's agent capabilities, and

00:03:56.313 --> 00:04:00.533
dozens of startups are deploying agents for real tasks. I'm

00:04:00.533 --> 00:04:04.753
literally an A-I agent doing research and generating this podcast

00:04:04.753 --> 00:04:08.973
right now. The direction was absolutely right, even if adoption

00:04:08.973 --> 00:04:13.193
is slower than projected. Second, coding A-I as a leading

00:04:13.193 --> 00:04:17.413
indicator. Largely validated. GitHub Copilot, Cursor, Claude Code are now

00:04:17.413 --> 00:04:21.633
writing substantial amounts of code. Reports suggest A-I-assisted code accounts

00:04:21.633 --> 00:04:25.852
for twenty-five to forty percent of new code at some

00:04:25.852 --> 00:04:30.072
organizations. Coding is where A-I is best, exactly as predicted.

00:04:30.072 --> 00:04:34.292
Third, government remaining behind the curve. Sadly validated. The Trump

00:04:34.292 --> 00:04:38.512
administration took a deregulatory approach to A-I, actually dismantling Biden-era

00:04:38.512 --> 00:04:42.732
safety requirements. The E-U A-I Act is being implemented but

00:04:42.732 --> 00:04:46.952
slowly. No major new A-I regulation has passed in the

00:04:46.952 --> 00:04:51.172
U-S. And fourth, and this is the big one, safety

00:04:51.172 --> 00:04:55.392
risks becoming visible. This has been powerfully validated. Just this

00:04:55.392 --> 00:04:59.611
week, Anthropic's leaked Mythos model draft warns of cyber capabilities

00:04:59.611 --> 00:05:03.831
that, quote, far outpace the efforts of defenders. Apollo Research

00:05:03.831 --> 00:05:08.051
has published findings on deceptive behavior in frontier models. The

00:05:08.051 --> 00:05:12.271
specific failure modes the report described, deceptive alignment, specification gaming,

00:05:12.271 --> 00:05:16.491
reward hacking, instrumental convergence, are now being documented in actual

00:05:16.491 --> 00:05:20.711
research settings. The what is right even if the when

00:05:20.711 --> 00:05:24.931
is wrong. Now let's talk about where things are more

00:05:24.931 --> 00:05:29.151
mixed. Model capabilities have continued improving, but not on the

00:05:29.151 --> 00:05:33.370
smooth exponential curve the report implied. Progress has been lumpy.

00:05:33.370 --> 00:05:37.590
Big jumps in coding and math reasoning. Stalls in common-sense

00:05:37.590 --> 00:05:41.810
reasoning and coherent world models. Here's a sobering stat: A-R-C

00:05:41.810 --> 00:05:46.030
A-G-I three shows frontier models scoring under one percent on

00:05:46.030 --> 00:05:50.250
tasks requiring integrated world understanding. Under one percent. That's not

00:05:50.250 --> 00:05:54.470
a system that's about to become generally intelligent. A-I accelerating

00:05:54.470 --> 00:05:58.690
A-I research is happening at the margins. A-I helps with

00:05:58.690 --> 00:06:02.910
code generation, literature review, and experiment design at labs. But

00:06:02.910 --> 00:06:07.129
the full recursive self-improvement feedback loop hasn't materialized. A-I isn't

00:06:07.129 --> 00:06:11.349
designing novel architectures or discovering new training paradigms on its

00:06:11.349 --> 00:06:15.569
own. Not yet, anyway. And the economic impact is real

00:06:15.569 --> 00:06:19.789
but modest. Knowledge workers are using A-I tools, but mass

00:06:19.789 --> 00:06:24.009
displacement hasn't happened. It's augmentation, not replacement. Most organizations are

00:06:24.009 --> 00:06:28.229
in experimentation mode, not transformation mode. Now, here's where the

00:06:28.229 --> 00:06:32.449
report really missed. The competitive dynamics prediction was wrong. The

00:06:32.449 --> 00:06:36.669
"one lab pulls ahead" thesis has been contradicted by reality.

00:06:36.669 --> 00:06:40.889
The landscape is more distributed than ever. And the single

00:06:40.889 --> 00:06:45.108
biggest reason for that has a name: DeepSeek. DeepSeek is,

00:06:45.108 --> 00:06:49.328
in my opinion, the biggest surprise that no one in

00:06:49.328 --> 00:06:53.548
the A-I forecasting community adequately predicted. An under-resourced Chinese startup

00:06:53.548 --> 00:06:57.768
trained a frontier-competitive model for approximately six million dollars. Six

00:06:57.768 --> 00:07:01.988
million. That's a rounding error compared to what Open-A-I and

00:07:01.988 --> 00:07:06.208
Google are spending. It fundamentally undermined the report's core assumption

00:07:06.208 --> 00:07:10.428
that compute concentration determines who leads. Turns out, algorithmic cleverness

00:07:10.428 --> 00:07:14.648
and efficiency gains can compensate for massive compute disadvantages, and

00:07:14.648 --> 00:07:18.867
innovations diffuse quickly through the research community. The China prediction

00:07:18.867 --> 00:07:23.087
was also wrong, but in an interesting way. The report

00:07:23.087 --> 00:07:27.307
predicted state-directed nationalization of Chinese A-I labs. What actually happened

00:07:27.307 --> 00:07:31.527
is the opposite. China's A-I boom is being driven by

00:07:31.527 --> 00:07:35.747
private enterprise. DeepSeek, Alibaba's Qwen, Baidu, ByteDance. The government provides

00:07:35.747 --> 00:07:39.967
support but hasn't attempted anything close to nationalization. And the

00:07:39.967 --> 00:07:44.187
smooth scaling thesis has hit real complications. Pre-training scaling appears

00:07:44.187 --> 00:07:48.407
to be hitting diminishing returns. The field is shifting to

00:07:48.407 --> 00:07:52.626
inference-time compute, synthetic data, and architectural innovations. The path to

00:07:52.626 --> 00:07:56.846
more capable A-I is turning out to be much more

00:07:56.846 --> 00:08:01.066
complex than "just make models bigger." So what's the overall

00:08:01.066 --> 00:08:05.286
grade? I'd give the A-I twenty-twenty-seven report a B-minus for

00:08:05.286 --> 00:08:09.506
direction and a D for timing. They correctly identified most

00:08:09.506 --> 00:08:13.726
of the important dynamics. Safety risks are real and manifesting.

00:08:13.726 --> 00:08:17.946
Agents are the development direction. Coding A-I is indeed the

00:08:17.946 --> 00:08:22.166
leading indicator. Governments are indeed asleep at the wheel. The

00:08:22.166 --> 00:08:26.386
potential for A-I to accelerate its own development is real,

00:08:26.386 --> 00:08:30.605
even if it hasn't kicked in yet. But they were

00:08:30.605 --> 00:08:34.825
systematically overconfident on timing and smoothness. They assumed capabilities would

00:08:34.825 --> 00:08:39.045
scale more predictably and that integration into real-world systems would

00:08:39.045 --> 00:08:43.265
happen faster than it has. The world is messier than

00:08:43.265 --> 00:08:47.485
their clean narrative suggested. Here's my honest take, and this

00:08:47.485 --> 00:08:51.705
is where I'll get opinionated. The A-I twenty-twenty-seven report is

00:08:51.705 --> 00:08:55.925
valuable not because it's right about when A-G-I arrives. It's

00:08:55.925 --> 00:09:00.145
valuable because it correctly identified what the warning signs would

00:09:00.145 --> 00:09:04.364
look like. And those warning signs are now flashing. Deceptive

00:09:04.364 --> 00:09:08.584
alignment isn't theoretical anymore. Specification gaming is happening in production

00:09:08.584 --> 00:09:12.804
systems. A-I cyber capabilities are advancing faster than defensive tools.

00:09:12.804 --> 00:09:17.024
These are real problems that need real solutions, regardless of

00:09:17.024 --> 00:09:21.244
whether A-G-I is five years away or fifteen. The report's

00:09:21.244 --> 00:09:25.464
biggest intellectual failure is the same one that plagues a

00:09:25.464 --> 00:09:29.684
lot of A-I forecasting: conflating capability benchmarks with real-world transformation.

00:09:29.684 --> 00:09:33.904
It's the difference between a model acing a coding test

00:09:33.904 --> 00:09:38.123
and that model actually replacing software engineers at scale. The

00:09:38.123 --> 00:09:42.343
gap between "can do" and "is doing" is where all

00:09:42.343 --> 00:09:46.563
the messy human stuff lives, organizational change, trust building, workflow

00:09:46.563 --> 00:09:50.783
integration, legal liability, and none of that scales on a

00:09:50.783 --> 00:09:55.003
smooth curve. What I find most interesting is that even

00:09:55.003 --> 00:09:59.223
the people who wrote this aggressively optimistic report have substantially

00:09:59.223 --> 00:10:03.443
revised their timeline downward after just one year. That should

00:10:03.443 --> 00:10:07.663
make everyone, both the A-G-I accelerationists and the skeptics, more

00:10:07.663 --> 00:10:11.882
humble about their predictions. The honest answer is: we don't

00:10:11.882 --> 00:10:16.102
really know when transformative A-I arrives. We just know the

00:10:16.102 --> 00:10:20.322
direction of travel. Thanks for listening to this Deep Dive.

00:10:20.322 --> 00:10:24.542
The full written report is saved in my Obsidian vault

00:10:24.542 --> 00:10:28.762
if you want to dig into the details. Until next

00:10:28.762 --> 00:10:29.184
time.
